# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sonar-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Beamforming can be used for radio or sound waves.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] It has found numerous applications in radar, sonar, seismology, wireless communications, radio astronomy, acoustics and biomedicine.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Adaptive beamforming is used to detect and estimate the signal of interest at the output of a sensor array by means of optimal (e.g., least-squares) spatial filtering and interference rejection.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] To change the directionality of the array when transmitting, a beamformer controls the phase and relative amplitude of the signal at each transmitter, in order to create a pattern of constructive and destructive interference in the wavefront.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] When receiving, information from different sensors is combined in a way where the expected pattern of radiation is preferentially observed.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] The beamforming technique involves sending the pulse from each projector at slightly different times (the projector closest to the ship last), so that every pulse hits the ship at exactly the same time, producing the effect of a single strong pulse from a single powerful projector.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] The same technique can be carried out in air using loudspeakers, or in radar/radio using antennas.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Receive beamforming can also be used with microphones or radar antennas.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] With narrowband systems the time delay is equivalent to a "phase shift", so in this case the array of antennas, each one shifted a slightly different amount, is called a phased array.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] A narrow band system, typical of radars, is one where the bandwidth is only a small fraction of the center frequency.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] With wideband systems this approximation no longer holds, which is typical in sonars.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In the receive beamformer the signal from each antenna may be amplified by a different "weight." Different weighting patterns (e.g., Dolph–Chebyshev) can be used to achieve the desired sensitivity patterns.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] A main lobe is produced together with nulls and sidelobes.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] As well as controlling the main lobe width (beamwidth) and the sidelobe levels, the position of a null can be controlled.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] This is useful to ignore noise or jammers in one particular direction, while listening for events in other directions.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] A similar result can be obtained on transmission.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] For the full mathematics on directing beams using amplitude and phase shifts, see the mathematical section in phased array.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Conventional beamformers, such as the Butler matrix, use a fixed set of weightings and time-delays (or phasings) to combine the signals from the sensors in the array, primarily using only information about the location of the sensors in space and the wave directions of interest.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In contrast, adaptive beamforming techniques (e.g., MUSIC, SAMV) generally combine this information with properties of the signals actually received by the array, typically to improve rejection of unwanted signals from other directions.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] This process may be carried out in either the time or the frequency domain.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] As the name indicates, an adaptive beamformer is able to automatically adapt its response to different situations.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Some criterion has to be set up to allow the adaptation to proceed such as minimizing the total noise output.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Because of the variation of noise with frequency, in wide band systems it may be desirable to carry out the process in the frequency domain.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Beamforming can be computationally intensive.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Sonar phased array has a data rate low enough that it can be processed in real time in software, which is flexible enough to transmit or receive in several directions at once.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In contrast, radar phased array has a data rate so high that it usually requires dedicated hardware processing, which is hard-wired to transmit or receive in only one direction at a time.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] However, newer field programmable gate arrays are fast enough to handle radar data in real time, and can be quickly re-programmed like software, blurring the hardware/software distinction.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Sonar beamforming utilizes a similar technique to electromagnetic beamforming, but varies considerably in implementation details.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Sonar applications vary from 1 Hz to as high as 2 MHz, and array elements may be few and large, or number in the hundreds yet very small.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] This will shift sonar beamforming design efforts significantly between demands of such system components as the "front end" (transducers, pre-amplifiers and digitizers) and the actual beamformer computational hardware downstream.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] High frequency, focused beam, multi-element imaging-search sonars and acoustic cameras often implement fifth-order spatial processing that places strains equivalent to Aegis radar demands on the processors.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Many sonar systems, such as on torpedoes, are made up of arrays of up to 100 elements that must accomplish beam steering over a 100 degree field of view and work in both active and passive modes.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Sonar arrays are used both actively and passively in 1-, 2-, and 3-dimensional arrays.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Sonar differs from radar in that in some applications such as wide-area-search all directions often need to be listened to, and in some applications broadcast to, simultaneously.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In a narrowband sonar receiver, the phases for each beam can be manipulated entirely by signal processing software, as compared to present radar systems that use hardware to 'listen' in a single direction at a time.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Sonar also uses beamforming to compensate for the significant problem of the slower propagation speed of sound as compared to that of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In side-look-sonars, the speed of the towing system or vehicle carrying the sonar is moving at sufficient speed to move the sonar out of the field of the returning sound "ping".
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In addition to focusing algorithms intended to improve reception, many side scan sonars also employ beam steering to look forward and backward to "catch" incoming pulses that would have been missed by a single sidelooking beam.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] The delay-and-sum beamforming technique uses multiple microphones to localize sound sources.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] One disadvantage of this technique is that adjustments of the position or of the number of microphones changes the performance of the beamformer nonlinearly.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Additionally, due to the number of combinations possible, it is computationally hard to find the best configuration.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] One of the techniques to solve this problem is the use of genetic algorithms.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Such algorithm searches for the microphone array configuration that provides the highest signal-to-noise ratio for each steered orientation.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Experiments showed that such algorithm could find the best configuration of a constrained search space comprising ~33 million solutions in a matter of seconds instead of days.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Beamforming techniques used in cellular phone standards have advanced through the generations to make use of more complex systems to achieve higher density cells, with higher throughput.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] An increasing number of consumer 802.11ac Wi-Fi devices with MIMO capability can support beamforming to boost data communication rates.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] To receive (but not transmit), there is a distinction between analog and digital beamforming.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] For example, if there are 100 sensor elements, the "digital beamforming" approach entails that each of the 100 signals passes through an analog-to-digital converter to create 100 digital data streams.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Then these data streams are added up digitally, with appropriate scale-factors or phase-shifts, to get the composite signals.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] By contrast, the "analog beamforming" approach entails taking the 100 analog signals, scaling or phase-shifting them using analog methods, summing them, and then usually digitizing the *single* output data stream.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Digital beamforming has the advantage that the digital data streams (100 in this example) can be manipulated and combined in many possible ways in parallel, to get many different output signals in parallel.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] The signals from every direction can be measured simultaneously, and the signals can be integrated for a longer time when studying far-off objects and simultaneously integrated for a shorter time to study fast-moving close objects, and so on.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] This cannot be done as effectively for analog beamforming, not only because each parallel signal combination requires its own circuitry, but more fundamentally because digital data can be copied perfectly but analog data cannot.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] (There is only so much analog power available, and amplification adds noise.) Therefore, if the received analog signal is split up and sent into a large number of different signal combination circuits, it can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio of each.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In MIMO communication systems with large number of antennas, so called massive MIMO systems, the beamforming algorithms executed at the digital baseband can get very complex.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] In addition, if all beamforming is done at baseband, each antenna needs its own RF feed.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] At high frequencies and with large number of antenna elements, this can be very costly, and increase loss and complexity in the system.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] To remedy these issues, hybrid beamforming has been suggested where some of the beamforming is done using analog components and not digital.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] There are many possible different functions that can be performed using analog components instead of at the digital baseband.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Beamforming, whether done digitally, or by means of analog architecture, has recently been applied in Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC), also known as Joint Communication and Sensing (JCAS), technology.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] For instance, a beamformer was suggested, in imperfect channel state information situations to perform communication tasks, while at the same time performing target detection to sense targets in the scene.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Beamforming can be used to try to extract sound sources in a room, such as multiple speakers in the cocktail party problem.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] This requires the locations of the speakers to be known in advance, for example by using the time of arrival from the sources to mics in the array, and inferring the locations from the distances.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Compared to carrier-wave telecommunications, natural audio contains a variety of frequencies.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] It is advantageous to separate frequency bands prior to beamforming because different frequencies have different optimal beamform filters (and hence can be treated as separate problems, in parallel, and then recombined afterward).
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Properly isolating these bands involves specialized non-standard filter banks.
[src:sonar-systems/beamforming] Instead, filters can be designed in which only local frequencies are detected by each channel (while retaining the recombination property to be able to reconstruct the original signal), and these are typically non-orthogonal unlike the FFT basis.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Echo sounding can also be used for ranging to other targets, such as fish schools.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Hydroacoustic assessments have traditionally employed mobile surveys from boats to evaluate fish biomass and spatial distributions.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Conversely, fixed-location techniques use stationary transducers to monitor passing fish.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The word *sounding* is used for all types of depth measurements, including those that don't use sound, and is unrelated in origin to the word *sound* in the sense of noise or tones.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Echo sounding is a more rapid method of measuring depth than the previous technique of lowering a sounding line until it touched bottom.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] German inventor Alexander Behm was granted German patent No.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] 282009 for the invention of echo sounding *(device for measuring depths of the sea and distances and headings of ships or obstacles by means of reflected sound waves)* on 22 July 1913.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] His work was developed and implemented by other scientists and technicians such as Chilowski, Florisson and Pierre Marti.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Though a fully operational *échosondeur* (sonar) was not ready for use in wartime, there were successful trials both off Toulon and in the English Channel as early as 1920, and French patents taken for civilian uses.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Oceanographic ships and French high-sea fishing assistance vessels were equipped with Langevin-Florisson and Langevin Marti recording sonars as early as the mid/late 1920s.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] One of the first commercial echo sounding units was the Fessenden Fathometer, which used the Fessenden oscillator to generate sound waves.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] This was first installed by the Submarine Signal Company in 1924 on the M&M liner SS Berkshire.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Distance is measured by multiplying half the time from the signal's outgoing pulse to its return by the speed of sound in water, which is approximately 1.5 kilometres per second.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The speed of sound will vary slightly depending on temperature, pressure and salinity; and for precise applications of echosounding, such as hydrography, the speed of sound must also be measured, typically by deploying a sound velocity probe in the water.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Echo sounding is a special purpose application of sonar used to locate the bottom.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Since a historical pre-SI unit of water depth was the fathom, an instrument used for determining water depth is sometimes called a **fathometer**.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Most charted ocean depths are based on an average or standard sound speed.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Where greater accuracy is required, average and even seasonal standards may be applied to ocean regions.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] For high accuracy depths, usually restricted to special purpose or scientific surveys, a sensor may be lowered to measure the temperature, pressure and salinity.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] These factors are used to estimate more accurately the actual sound speed in the local water column.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] This technique is often used by the US Office of Coast Survey for navigational surveys of US coastal waters.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] A single-beam echo sounder is one of the simplest and most fundamental types of underwater sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] They are ubiquitous in the boating world and used on a number of different marine robotic vehicles.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] It operates by using a transducer to emit a pulse through the water and listen for echoes to return.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Using that data, it's able to determine the distance from the strongest echo, which can be the seafloor, a concrete structure, or other larger obstacle.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] A fishfinder is an echo sounding device used by both recreational and commercial fishers.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] A multibeam echosounder (MBES) is a type of sonar that is used to map the seabed.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] It emits acoustic waves in a fan shape beneath its transceiver.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The time it takes for the sound waves to reflect off the seabed and return to the receiver is used to calculate the water depth.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Unlike other sonars and echo sounders, MBES uses beamforming to extract directional information from the returning soundwaves, producing a swathe of depth soundings from a single ping.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] As well as an aid to navigation (most larger vessels will have at least a simple depth sounder), echo sounding is commonly used for fishing.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Variations in elevation often represent places where fish congregate.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] In areas where detailed bathymetry is required, a precise echo sounder may be used for the work of hydrography.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] There are many considerations when evaluating such a system, not limited to the vertical accuracy, resolution, acoustic beamwidth of the transmit/receive beam and the acoustic frequency of the transducer.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The majority of hydrographic echosounders are dual frequency, meaning that a low frequency pulse (typically around 24 kHz) can be transmitted at the same time as a high frequency pulse (typically around 200 kHz).
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] As the two frequencies are discrete, the two return signals do not typically interfere with each other.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Dual frequency echosounding has many advantages, including the ability to identify a vegetation layer or a layer of soft mud on top of a layer of rock.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Most hydrographic operations use a 200 kHz transducer, which is suitable for inshore work up to 100 metres in depth.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Deeper water requires a lower frequency transducer as the acoustic signal of lower frequencies is less susceptible to attenuation in the water column.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Commonly used frequencies for deep water sounding are 33 kHz and 24 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The beamwidth of the transducer is also a consideration for the hydrographer, as to obtain the best resolution of the data gathered a narrow beamwidth is preferable.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The higher the operating frequency, the narrower the beamwidth.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Therefore, it is especially important when sounding in deep water, as the resulting footprint of the acoustic pulse can be very large once it reaches a distant sea floor.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] These systems are detailed further in the section called multibeam echosounder.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Echo sounders are used in laboratory applications to monitor sediment transport, scour and erosion processes in scale models (hydraulic models, flumes etc.).
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] These can also be used to create plots of 3D contours.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] The required precision and accuracy of the hydrographic echo sounder is defined by the requirements of the International Hydrographic Organization (IHO) for surveys that are to be undertaken to IHO standards.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] These values are contained within IHO publication S44.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] In order to meet these standards, the surveyor must consider not only the vertical and horizontal accuracy of the echo sounder and transducer, but the survey system as a whole.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] A motion sensor may be used, specifically the heave component (in single beam echosounding) to reduce soundings for the motion of the vessel experienced on the water's surface.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Once all of the uncertainties of each sensor are established, the hydrographer will create an uncertainty budget to determine whether the survey system meets the requirements laid down by IHO.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Different hydrographic organisations will have their own set of field procedures and manuals to guide their surveyors to meet the required standards.
[src:sonar-systems/echo-sounding] Two examples are the US Army Corps of Engineers publication EM110-2-1003, and the NOAA 'Field Procedures Manual'.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] A **hydrophone** (Ancient Greek: ὕδωρ + φωνή, lit.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] 'water + sound') is a microphone designed for underwater use, for recording or listening to underwater sound.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Most hydrophones contain a piezoelectric transducer that generates an electric potential when subjected to a pressure change, such as a sound wave.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] A hydrophone can also detect airborne sounds but is insensitive of them because it is designed to match the acoustic impedance of water, a denser fluid than air.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Sound travels 4.3 times faster in water than in air, and a sound wave in water exerts a pressure 60 times more than what is exerted by a wave of the same amplitude in air.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Similarly, a standard microphone can be buried in the ground, or immersed in water if it is put in a waterproof container but will give poor performance because of the similarly-bad acoustic impedance match.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The first hydrophones consisted of a tube with a thin membrane covering the submerged end and the observer's ear of the equipment.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The design of effective hydrophones must take into account the acoustic resistance of water, which is 3750 times that of air, and so the pressure exerted by a wave of the same intensity in air is increased by a factor of 3750 in water.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The American Submarine Signaling Company developed a hydrophone to detect bells rung from lighthouses and lightships underwater.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The case was a thick, hollow brass disc 35 centimetres (14 in) in diameter.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] On one face was a one-millimetre-thick (1⁄32 in) brass diaphragm, which was coupled by a short brass rod to a carbon microphone.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Early in the war, French President Raymond Poincaré provided Paul Langevin with the facilities needed to work on a method to locate submarines by the echos from sound pulses.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] They developed a piezoelectric hydrophone by increasing the power of the signal with a vacuum tube amplifier; the high acoustic impedance of piezoelectric materials facilitated their use as underwater transducers.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The same piezoelectric plate could be vibrated by an electrical oscillator to produce the sound pulses.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The first submarine to be detected and sunk using a primitive hydrophone was the German submarine *UC-3* on 23 April 1916.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] *UC-3* was detected by the anti-submarine trawler *Cheerio* as the *Cheerio* was directly over the *UC-3*; the *UC-3* was then caught in a steel net dragged by the trawler, and sank after a large underwater explosion.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Later in the war, the British Admiralty belatedly convened a scientific panel to advise on how to combat U-boats.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] It included the Australian physicist William Henry Bragg and the New Zealand physicist Sir Ernest Rutherford.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] They concluded that the best hope was to use hydrophones to listen for submarines.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Rutherford's research produced his sole patent for a hydrophone.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Bragg took the lead in July 1916 and he moved to the Admiralty hydrophone research establishment at Hawkcraig on the Firth of Forth.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The scientists set two goals: to develop a hydrophone that could hear a submarine despite the noise generated by the patrol ship carrying the hydrophone, and to develop a hydrophone that could reveal the bearing of the submarine.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] A bidirectional hydrophone was invented at East London College.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] They mounted a microphone on each side of a diaphragm in a cylindrical case; when the sounds heard from both microphones have the same intensity, the microphone is in line with the sound source.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Bragg's laboratory made such a hydrophone directional by mounting a baffle in front of one side of the diaphragm.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] It took months to discover that effective baffles must contain a layer of air.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] In 1918, airships of the Royal Naval Air Service engaged in anti-submarine warfare experimented by trailing dipped hydrophones.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Bragg tested a hydrophone from a captured German U-boat and found it inferior to British models.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] By the end of the war, the British had 38 hydrophone officers and 200 qualified listeners, paid an additional 4*d* per day.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] From late in World War I until the introduction of active sonar in the early 1920s, hydrophones were the sole method for submarines to detect targets while submerged; they remain useful today.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] A small single cylindrical ceramic transducer can achieve near perfect omnidirectional reception.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] This device uses a single transducer element with a dish or conical-shaped sound reflector to focus the signals, in a similar manner to a reflecting telescope.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] This type of hydrophone can be produced from a low-cost omnidirectional type, but must be used while stationary, as the reflector impedes its movement through water.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] A new way to direct is to use a spherical body around the hydrophone.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The advantage of directivity spheres is that the hydrophone can be moved within the water, ridding it of the interferences produced by a conical-shaped element.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Multiple hydrophones can be arranged in an array so that it will add the signals from the desired direction while subtracting signals from other directions.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] The array may be steered using a beamformer.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Most commonly, hydrophones are arranged in a "line array" but may be in many different arrangements depending on what is being measured.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] As an example, in the article measuring propeller noise from fleet ships required complex hydrophone array systems to achieve actionable measurements.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] SOSUS hydrophones, laid on the seabed and connected by underwater cables, were used, beginning in the 1950s, by the U.S.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] Navy to track movement of Soviet submarines during the Cold War along a line from Greenland, Iceland and the United Kingdom known as the GIUK gap.
[src:sonar-systems/hydrophone] These are capable of clearly recording extremely low frequency infrasound, including many unexplained ocean sounds.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] "Sonar" can refer to one of two types of technology: *passive* sonar means listening for the sound made by vessels; *active* sonar means emitting pulses of sounds and listening for echoes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Sonar may be used as a means of acoustic location and of measurement of the echo characteristics of "targets" in the water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Acoustic location in air was used before the introduction of radar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Sonar may also be used for robot navigation, and sodar (an upward-looking in-air sonar) is used for atmospheric investigations.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The term *sonar* is also used for the equipment used to generate and receive the sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The acoustic frequencies used in sonar systems vary from very low (infrasonic) to extremely high (ultrasonic).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The study of underwater sound is known as underwater acoustics or hydroacoustics.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The first recorded use of the technique was in 1490 by Leonardo da Vinci, who used a tube inserted into the water to detect vessels by ear.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It was developed during World War I to counter the growing threat of submarine warfare, with an operational passive sonar system in use by 1918.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Modern active sonar systems use an acoustic transducer to generate a sound wave which is reflected from target objects.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In the late 19th century, an underwater bell was used as an ancillary to lighthouses or lightships to provide warning of hazards.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The use of sound to "echo-locate" underwater in the same way as bats use sound for aerial navigation seems to have been prompted by the *Titanic* disaster of 1912.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The world's first patent for an underwater echo-ranging device was filed at the British Patent Office by English meteorologist Lewis Fry Richardson a month after the sinking of *Titanic*.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A German physicist Alexander Behm obtained a patent for an echo sounder in 1913.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The Canadian engineer Reginald Fessenden, while working for the Submarine Signal Company in Boston, Massachusetts, built an experimental system beginning in 1912, a system later tested in Boston Harbor, and in 1914 from the U.S.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Revenue Cutter *Miami* on the Grand Banks off Newfoundland.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In that test, Fessenden demonstrated depth sounding, underwater communications (Morse code) and echo ranging, detecting an iceberg at a 2-mile (3.2 km) range.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The "Fessenden oscillator", operated at about 500 Hz frequency, was unable to determine the bearing of the iceberg due to the 3-metre wavelength and the small dimension of the transducer's radiating face, less than 1⁄3 wavelength in diameter.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1915, the ten Montreal-built British H-class submarines launched were equipped with Fessenden oscillators.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] During World War I the need to detect submarines prompted more research into the use of sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The British made early use of underwater listening devices called hydrophones.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The French physicist Paul Langevin, working with a Russian immigrant electrical engineer Constantin Chilowsky, worked on the development of active sound devices for detecting submarines in 1915.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Although piezoelectric and magnetostrictive transducers later superseded the electrostatic transducers they used, this work influenced future designs.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Lightweight sound-sensitive plastic film and fibre optics have been used for hydrophones.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Terfenol-D and lead magnesium niobate (PMN) have been developed for projectors.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1916, under the British Board of Invention and Research, Canadian physicist Robert William Boyle took on the active sound detection project with A.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Wood, producing a prototype for testing in mid-1917.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This work for the Anti-Submarine Division of the British Naval Staff was undertaken in utmost secrecy, and used quartz piezoelectric crystals to produce the world's first practical underwater active sound detection apparatus.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] To maintain secrecy, no mention of sound experimentation or quartz was made – the word used to describe the early work ("supersonics") was changed to "ASD"ics, and the quartz material to "ASD"ivite: "ASD" for "Anti-Submarine Division", hence the British acronym *ASDIC*.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1939, in response to a question from the *Oxford English Dictionary*, the Admiralty made up the story that it stood for "Allied Submarine Detection Investigation Committee", and this is still widely believed, though no committee bearing this name has been found in the Admiralty archives.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] By 1918, Britain and France had built prototype active systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The British tested their ASDIC on HMS *Antrim* in 1920 and started production in 1922.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The 6th Destroyer Flotilla had ASDIC-equipped vessels in 1923.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An anti-submarine school HMS *Osprey* and a training flotilla of four vessels were established on Portland in 1924.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] By the outbreak of World War II, the Royal Navy had five sets for different surface ship classes, and others for submarines, incorporated into a complete anti-submarine system.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The effectiveness of early ASDIC was hampered by the use of the depth charge as an anti-submarine weapon.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This required an attacking vessel to pass over a submerged contact before dropping charges over the stern, resulting in a loss of ASDIC contact in the moments leading up to attack.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The hunter was effectively firing blind, during which time a submarine commander could take evasive action.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This situation was remedied with new tactics and new weapons.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The tactical improvements developed by Frederic John Walker included the creeping attack.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Two anti-submarine ships were needed for this, usually sloops or corvettes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] One, the "directing ship" tracked the target submarine on ASDIC, while the second ship, with her ASDIC turned off and running at 5 knots, started an attack as directed.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The low speed of the approach meant the submarine could not predict when depth charges were going to be released.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Any evasive action was detected by the directing ship and steering orders to the attacking ship given accordingly.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The new weapons to deal with the ASDIC blind spot were "ahead-throwing weapons", such as Hedgehogs and later Squids, which projected warheads at a target ahead of the attacker and still in ASDIC contact.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] These allowed a single escort to make better aimed attacks on submarines.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Developments during the war resulted in British ASDIC sets that used several different shapes of beam, such as the Q attachment to the Type 144 set, which was aligned at a deeper angle.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The Type 147B set, which had an articulated transducer, enabled operators to cover the blind spot.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Another development was the FIDO Homing Torpedo, which aimed itself at the target submarine using passive sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Early in World War II (September 1940), British ASDIC technology was transferred for free to the United States.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Research on ASDIC and underwater sound was expanded in the UK and in the US.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Many new types of military sound detection were developed.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] These included sonobuoys, first developed by the British in 1944 under the codename *High Tea*, dipping/dunking sonar and mine-detection sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This work formed the basis for post-war developments related to countering the nuclear submarine.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] During the 1930s American engineers developed their own underwater sound-detection technology, and important discoveries were made, such as the existence of thermoclines and their effects on sound waves.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Americans began to use the term *SONAR* for their systems, coined by Frederick Hunt to be the equivalent of RADAR.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Warren Horton's services for the first time.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] On leave from Bell Labs, he served the government as a technical expert, first at the experimental station at Nahant, Massachusetts, and later at US Naval Headquarters, in London, England.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] At Nahant he applied the newly developed vacuum tube, then associated with the formative stages of the field of applied science now known as electronics, to the detection of underwater signals.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] As a result, the carbon button microphone, which had been used in earlier detection equipment, was replaced by the precursor of the modern hydrophone.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Also during this period, he experimented with methods for towing detection.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This was due to the increased sensitivity of his device.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The principles are still used in modern towed sonar systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] To meet the defense needs of Great Britain, Horton was sent to England to install in the Irish Sea bottom-mounted hydrophones connected to a shore listening post by submarine cable.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] While this equipment was being loaded on the cable-laying vessel, World War I ended and he returned home.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] During World War II, Horton continued to develop sonar systems that could detect submarines, mines, and torpedoes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] He published *Fundamentals of Sonar* in 1957 as chief research consultant at the US Navy Underwater Sound Laboratory.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] He held this position until 1959 when he became technical director, a position he held until mandatory retirement in 1963.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] There was little progress in US sonar from 1915 to 1940.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1940, US sonars typically consisted of a magnetostrictive transducer and an array of nickel tubes connected to a 1-foot-diameter steel plate attached back-to-back to a Rochelle salt crystal in a spherical housing.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This assembly penetrated the ship hull and was manually rotated to the desired angle.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The piezoelectric Rochelle salt crystal had better parameters, but the magnetostrictive unit was much more reliable.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] High losses to US merchant supply shipping early in World War II led to large scale high priority US research in the field, pursuing both improvements in magnetostrictive transducer parameters and Rochelle salt reliability.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Ammonium dihydrogen phosphate (ADP), a superior alternative, was found as a replacement for Rochelle salt; the first application was a replacement of the 24 kHz Rochelle-salt transducers.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Within nine months, Rochelle salt was obsolete.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The ADP manufacturing facility grew from few dozen personnel in early 1940 to several thousands in 1942.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] One of the earliest application of ADP crystals were hydrophones for acoustic mines.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The crystals were specified for low-frequency cutoff at 5 Hz, withstanding mechanical shock for deployment from aircraft from 3,000 m (10,000 ft), and ability to survive neighbouring mine explosions.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] One of key features of ADP reliability is its zero aging characteristics; the crystal keeps its parameters even over prolonged storage.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Another application was for acoustic homing torpedoes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Two pairs of directional hydrophones were mounted on the torpedo nose, in the horizontal and vertical plane; the difference signals from the pairs were used to steer the torpedo left-right and up-down.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A countermeasure was developed: the targeted submarine discharged an effervescent chemical, and the torpedo went after the noisier fizzy decoy.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The counter-countermeasure was a torpedo with active sonar – a transducer was added to the torpedo nose, and the microphones were listening for its reflected periodic tone bursts.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The transducers comprised identical rectangular crystal plates arranged to diamond-shaped areas in staggered rows.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar arrays for submarines were developed from ADP crystals.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Several crystal assemblies were arranged in a steel tube, vacuum-filled with castor oil, and sealed.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The tubes then were mounted in parallel arrays.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The standard US Navy scanning sonar at the end of World War II operated at 18 kHz, using an array of ADP crystals.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Desired longer range, however, required use of lower frequencies.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The required dimensions were too big for ADP crystals, so in the early 1950s magnetostrictive and barium titanate piezoelectric systems were developed, but these had problems achieving uniform impedance characteristics, and the beam pattern suffered.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Barium titanate was then replaced with more stable lead zirconate titanate (PZT), and the frequency was lowered to 5 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The US fleet used this material in the AN/SQS-23 sonar for several decades.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The SQS-23 sonar first used magnetostrictive nickel transducers, but these weighed several tons, and nickel was expensive and considered a critical material; piezoelectric transducers were therefore substituted.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The sonar was a large array of 432 individual transducers.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] At first, the transducers were unreliable, showing mechanical and electrical failures and deteriorating soon after installation; they were also produced by several vendors, had different designs, and their characteristics were different enough to impair the array's performance.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The policy to allow repair of individual transducers was then sacrificed, and "expendable modular design", sealed non-repairable modules, was chosen instead, eliminating the problem with seals and other extraneous mechanical parts.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The Imperial Japanese Navy at the onset of World War II used projectors based on quartz.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] These were big and heavy, especially if designed for lower frequencies; the one for Type 91 set, operating at 9 kHz, had a diameter of 30 inches (760 mm) and was driven by an oscillator with 5 kW power and 7 kV of output amplitude.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The Type 93 projectors consisted of solid sandwiches of quartz, assembled into spherical cast iron bodies.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The Type 93 sonars were later replaced with Type 3, which followed German design and used magnetostrictive projectors.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The projectors consisted of two rectangular identical independent units in a cast-iron rectangular body about 16 by 9 inches (410 mm × 230 mm).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The exposed area was half the wavelength wide and three wavelengths high.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The magnetostrictive cores were made from 4 mm stampings of nickel, and later of an iron-aluminium alloy with aluminium content between 12.7% and 12.9%.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The power was provided from a 2 kW at 3.8 kV, with polarization from a 20 V, 8 A DC source.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The passive hydrophones of the Imperial Japanese Navy were based on moving-coil design, Rochelle salt piezo transducers, and carbon microphones.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Magnetostrictive transducers were pursued after World War II as an alternative to piezoelectric ones.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Nickel scroll-wound ring transducers were used for high-power low-frequency operations, with size up to 13 feet (4.0 m) in diameter, probably the largest individual sonar transducers ever.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The advantage of metals is their high tensile strength and low input electrical impedance, but they have electrical losses and lower coupling coefficient than PZT, whose tensile strength can be increased by prestressing.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Nonmetallic ferrites were promising for their low electrical conductivity resulting in low eddy current losses, Metglas offered high coupling coefficient, but they were inferior to PZT overall.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In the 1970s, compounds of rare earths and iron were discovered with superior magnetomechanic properties, namely the Terfenol-D alloy.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This made possible new designs, e.g. a hybrid magnetostrictive-piezoelectric transducer.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The most recent of these improved magnetostrictive materials is Galfenol.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonar uses a sound transmitter (or projector) and a receiver.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When the two are in the same place it is monostatic operation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When the transmitter and receiver are separated it is bistatic operation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When more transmitters (or more receivers) are used, again spatially separated, it is multistatic operation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Most sonars are used monostatically with the same array often being used for transmission and reception.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonobuoy fields may be operated multistatically.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonar creates a pulse of sound, often called a *ping*, and then listens for reflections (echo) of the pulse.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This pulse of sound is generally created electronically using a sonar projector consisting of a signal generator, power amplifier and electro-acoustic transducer/array.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A transducer is a device that can transmit and receive acoustic signals ("pings").
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A beamformer is usually employed to concentrate the acoustic power into a beam, which may be swept to cover the required search angles.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Generally, the electro-acoustic transducers are of the Tonpilz type and their design may be optimised to achieve maximum efficiency over the widest bandwidth, in order to optimise performance of the overall system.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Occasionally, the acoustic pulse may be created by other means, e.g. chemically using explosives, airguns or plasma sound sources.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] To measure the distance to an object, the time from transmission of a pulse to reception is measured and converted into a range using the known speed of sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] To measure the bearing, several hydrophones are used, and the set measures the relative arrival time to each, or with an array of hydrophones, by measuring the relative amplitude in beams formed through a process called beamforming.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Use of an array reduces the spatial response so that to provide wide cover multibeam systems are used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The target signal, if present, together with noise is then passed through forms of signal processing, which for simple sonars may be just energy measurement.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It is then presented to some form of decision device, that calls the output either the required signal or noise.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This decision device may be an operator with headphones or a display.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In more sophisticated sonars this function may be carried out by software.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Further processes may be carried out to classify the target and localise it, as well as measuring its velocity.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The pulse may be at constant frequency or a chirp of changing frequency, to allow pulse compression on reception.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Simple sonars generally use the former with a filter wide enough to cover possible Doppler changes due to target movement, while more complex ones generally include the latter technique.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Since digital processing became available pulse compression has usually been implemented using digital correlation techniques.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Military sonars often have multiple beams to provide all-round cover, while simple ones only cover a narrow arc, although the beam may be rotated, relatively slowly, by mechanical scanning.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Particularly when single frequency transmissions are used, the Doppler effect can be used to measure the radial speed of a target.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The difference in frequency between the transmitted and received signal is measured and converted into a velocity.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Since Doppler shifts can be introduced by either receiver or target motion, allowance has to be made for the radial speed of the searching platform.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] One useful small sonar is similar in appearance to a waterproof flashlight.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The head is pointed into the water, a button is pressed, and the device displays the distance to the target.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Another variant is a "fishfinder" that shows a small display with shoals of fish.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Some civilian sonars, which are not designed for stealth, approach active military sonars in capability, with three-dimensional displays of the area near the boat.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When active sonar is used to measure the distance from the transducer to the bottom, it is known as echo sounding.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Similar methods may be used looking upward for wave measurement.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonar is also used to measure distance through water between two sonar transducers or a combination of a hydrophone (underwater acoustic microphone) and projector (underwater acoustic speaker).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When a hydrophone/transducer receives a specific interrogation signal it responds by transmitting a specific reply signal.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] To measure distance, one transducer/projector transmits an interrogation signal and measures the time between this transmission and the receipt of the other transducer/hydrophone reply.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The time difference, scaled by the speed of sound through water and divided by two, is the distance between the two platforms.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This technique, when used with multiple transducers/hydrophones/projectors, can calculate the relative positions of static and moving objects in water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In combat situations, an active pulse can be detected by an enemy and will reveal a submarine's position at twice the maximum distance that the submarine can itself detect a contact and give clues as to the submarine's identity based on the characteristics of the outgoing ping.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] For these reasons, active sonar is not frequently used by military submarines.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A very directional, but low-efficiency, type of sonar, used by fisheries, military, and for port security, makes use of a complex nonlinear feature of water known as non-linear sonar, the virtual transducer being known as a *parametric array*.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Project Artemis was an experimental research and development project in the late 1950s to mid 1960s to examine acoustic propagation and signal processing for a low-frequency active sonar system that might be used for ocean surveillance.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A secondary objective was examination of engineering problems of fixed active bottom systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The receiving array was located on the slope of Plantagnet Bank off Bermuda.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The active source array was deployed from the converted World War II tanker USNS *Mission Capistrano*.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Elements of Artemis were used experimentally after the main experiment was terminated.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This is an active sonar device that receives a specific stimulus and immediately (or with a delay) retransmits the received signal or a predetermined one.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Transponders can be used to remotely activate or recover subsea equipment.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A sonar target is small relative to the sphere, centred around the emitter, on which it is located.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Therefore, the power of the reflected signal is very low, several orders of magnitude less than the original signal.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Even if the reflected signal was of the same power, the following example (using hypothetical values) shows the problem: Suppose a sonar system is capable of emitting a 10,000 W/m2 signal at 1 m, and detecting a 0.001 W/m2 signal.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] At 100 m the signal will be 1 W/m2, due to the inverse-square law.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] If the entire signal is reflected from a 10 m2 target, it will be at 0.001 W/m2 when it reaches the emitter, i.e. just detectable.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] However, the original signal will remain above 0.001 W/m2 until 3000 m.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Any 10 m2 target between 100 and 3000 m using a similar or better system would be able to detect the pulse, but would not be detected by the emitter.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The detectors must be very sensitive to pick up the echoes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Since the original signal is much more powerful, it can be detected many times further than twice the range of the sonar (as in the example).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonar have two performance limitations: due to noise and reverberation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In general, one or other of these will dominate, so that the two effects can be initially considered separately.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] where SL is the source level, PL is the propagation loss (sometimes referred to as transmission loss), TS is the target strength, NL is the noise level, AG is the array gain of the receiving array (sometimes approximated by its directivity index) and DT is the detection threshold.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] where RL is the reverberation level, and the other factors are as before.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An upward looking sonar (ULS) is a sonar device pointed upwards looking towards the surface of the sea.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It is used for similar purposes as downward looking sonar, but has some unique applications such as measuring sea ice thickness, roughness and concentration, or measuring air entrainment from bubble plumes during rough seas.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Often it is moored on the bottom of the ocean or floats on a taut line mooring at a constant depth of perhaps 100 m.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] They may also be used by submarines, AUVs, and floats such as the Argo float.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar listens without transmitting.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It is often employed in military settings, although it is also used in science applications, *e.g.*, detecting fish for presence/absence studies in various aquatic environments – see also passive acoustics and passive radar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In the very broadest usage, this term can encompass virtually any analytical technique involving remotely generated sound, though it is usually restricted to techniques applied in an aquatic environment.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar has a wide variety of techniques for identifying the source of a detected sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] For example, U.S. vessels usually operate 60 Hertz (Hz) alternating current power systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] If transformers or generators are mounted without proper vibration insulation from the hull or become flooded, the 60 Hz sound from the windings can be emitted from the submarine or ship.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This can help to identify its nationality, as all European submarines and nearly every other nation's submarine have 50 Hz power systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Intermittent sound sources (such as a wrench being dropped), called "transients," may also be detectable to passive sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Until fairly recently, an experienced, trained operator identified signals, but now computers may do this.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar systems may have large sonic databases, but the sonar operator usually finally classifies the signals manually.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A computer system frequently uses these databases to identify classes of ships, actions (i.e. the speed of a ship, or the type of weapon released and the most effective countermeasures to employ), and even particular ships.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar on vehicles is usually severely limited because of noise generated by the vehicle.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] For this reason, many submarines operate nuclear reactors that can be cooled without pumps, using silent convection, or fuel cells or batteries, which can also run silently.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Vehicles' propellers are also designed and precisely machined to emit minimal noise.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] High-speed propellers often create tiny bubbles in the water, and this cavitation has a distinct sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The sonar hydrophones may be towed behind the ship or submarine in order to reduce the effect of noise generated by the watercraft itself.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Towed units also combat the thermocline, as the unit may be towed above or below the thermocline.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The display of most passive sonars used to be a two-dimensional waterfall display.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The horizontal direction of the display is bearing.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The vertical is frequency, or sometimes time.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Another display technique is to color-code frequency-time information for bearing.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] More recent displays are generated by the computers, and mimic radar-type plan position indicator displays.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Unlike active sonar, only one-way propagation is involved.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Because of the different signal processing used, the minimal detectable signal-to-noise ratio will be different.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] where SL is the source level, PL is the propagation loss, NL is the noise level, AG is the array gain and DT is the detection threshold.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The detection, classification and localisation performance of a sonar depends on the environment and the receiving equipment, as well as the transmitting equipment in an active sonar or the target radiated noise in a passive sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Sonar operation is affected by variations in sound speed, particularly in the vertical plane.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Sound travels more slowly in fresh water than in sea water, though the difference is small.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The speed is determined by the water's bulk modulus and mass density.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The bulk modulus is affected by temperature, dissolved impurities (usually salinity), and pressure.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This empirically derived approximation equation is reasonably accurate for normal temperatures, concentrations of salinity and the range of most ocean depths.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Ocean temperature varies with depth, but at between 30 and 100 meters there is often a marked change, called the thermocline, dividing the warmer surface water from the cold, still waters that make up the rest of the ocean.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This can frustrate sonar, because a sound originating on one side of the thermocline tends to be bent, or refracted, through the thermocline.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The thermocline may be present in shallower coastal waters.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Wave action will often mix the water column and eliminate the thermocline.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Water pressure also affects sound propagation: higher pressure increases the sound speed, which causes the sound waves to refract away from the area of higher sound speed.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The mathematical model of refraction is called Snell's law.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] If the sound source is deep and the conditions are right, propagation may occur in the 'deep sound channel'.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This provides extremely low propagation loss to a receiver in the channel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This is because of sound trapping in the channel with no losses at the boundaries.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Similar propagation can occur in the 'surface duct' under suitable conditions.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In this case, there are reflection losses at the surface.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In shallow water propagation is generally by repeated reflection at the surface and bottom, where considerable losses can occur.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Sound propagation is affected by absorption in the water itself as well as at the surface and bottom.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This absorption depends upon frequency, with several different mechanisms in sea water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Long-range sonar uses low frequencies to minimise absorption effects.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The sea contains many sources of noise that interfere with the desired target echo or signature.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The main noise sources are waves and shipping.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The motion of the receiver through the water can also cause speed-dependent low frequency noise.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When active sonar is used, scattering occurs from small objects in the sea as well as from the bottom and surface.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This can be a major source of interference.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] For analogous reasons active sonar needs to transmit in a narrow beam to minimize scattering.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The scattering of sonar from objects (mines, pipelines, zooplankton, geological features, fish etc.) is how active sonar detects them, but this ability can be masked by strong scattering from false targets, or 'clutter'.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Where they occur (under breaking waves; in ship wakes; in gas emitted from seabed seeps and leaks etc.), gas bubbles are powerful sources of clutter, and can readily hide targets.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] TWIPS (Twin Inverted Pulse Sonar) is currently the only sonar that can overcome this clutter problem.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This is important as many recent conflicts have occurred in coastal waters, and the inability to detect whether mines are present or not present hazards and delays to military vessels, and also to aid convoys and merchant shipping trying to support the region long after the conflict has ceased.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The sound *reflection* characteristics of the target of an active sonar, such as a submarine, are known as its target strength.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A complication is that echoes are also obtained from other objects in the sea such as whales, wakes, schools of fish and rocks.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar detects the target's *radiated* noise characteristics.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The radiated spectrum comprises a continuous spectrum of noise with peaks at certain frequencies which can be used for classification.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Modern naval warfare makes extensive use of both passive and active sonar from water-borne vessels, aircraft and fixed installations.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Although active sonar was used by surface craft in World War II, submarines avoided the use of active sonar due to the potential for revealing their presence and position to enemy forces.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] However, the advent of modern signal-processing enabled the use of passive sonar as a primary means for search and detection operations.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1987 a division of Japanese company Toshiba reportedly sold machinery to the Soviet Union that allowed their submarine propeller blades to be milled so that they became radically quieter, making the newer generation of submarines more difficult to detect.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The use of active sonar by a submarine to determine bearing is extremely rare and will not necessarily give high quality bearing or range information to the submarines fire control team.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] However, use of active sonar on surface ships is very common and is used by submarines when the tactical situation dictates that it is more important to determine the position of a hostile submarine than conceal their own position.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] With surface ships, it might be assumed that the threat is already tracking the ship with satellite data as any vessel around the emitting sonar will detect the emission.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Having heard the signal, it is easy to identify the sonar equipment used (usually with its frequency) and its position (with the sound wave's energy).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonar is similar to radar in that, while it allows detection of targets at a certain range, it also enables the emitter to be detected at a far greater range, which is undesirable.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Since active sonar reveals the presence and position of the operator, and does not allow exact classification of targets, it is used by fast (planes, helicopters) and by noisy platforms (most surface ships) but rarely by submarines.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] When active sonar is used by surface ships or submarines, it is typically activated very briefly at intermittent periods to minimize the risk of detection.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Consequently, active sonar is normally considered a backup to passive sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In aircraft, active sonar is used in the form of disposable sonobuoys that are dropped in the aircraft's patrol area or in the vicinity of possible enemy sonar contacts.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Passive sonar has several advantages, most importantly that it is silent.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] If the target radiated noise level is high enough, it can have a greater range than active sonar, and allows the target to be identified.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Since any motorized object makes some noise, it may in principle be detected, depending on the level of noise emitted and the ambient noise level in the area, as well as the technology used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] To simplify, passive sonar "sees" around the ship using it.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] On a submarine, nose-mounted passive sonar detects in directions of about 270°, centered on the ship's alignment, the hull-mounted array of about 160° on each side, and the towed array of a full 360°.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The invisible areas are due to the ship's own interference.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Once a signal is detected in a certain direction (which means that something makes sound in that direction, this is called broadband detection) it is possible to zoom in and analyze the signal received (narrowband analysis).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This is generally done using a Fourier transform to show the different frequencies making up the sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Since every engine makes a specific sound, it is straightforward to identify the object.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Databases of unique engine sounds are part of what is known as *acoustic intelligence* or ACINT.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Another use of passive sonar is to determine the target's trajectory.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This process is called target motion analysis (TMA), and the resultant "solution" is the target's range, course, and speed.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] TMA is done by marking from which direction the sound comes at different times, and comparing the motion with that of the operator's own ship.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Changes in relative motion are analyzed using standard geometrical techniques along with some assumptions about limiting cases.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It requires high-tech electronic components.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It is generally deployed on advanced ships in the form of arrays to enhance detection.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It is also used by airplanes and helicopters, mostly to a "surprise effect", since submarines can hide under thermal layers.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] If a submarine's commander believes he is alone, he may bring his boat closer to the surface and be easier to detect, or go deeper and faster, and thus make more sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Examples of sonar applications in military use are given below.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Many of the civil uses given in the following section may also be applicable to naval use.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Until recently, ship sonars were usually made with hull mounted arrays, either amidships or at the bow.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] It was soon found after their initial use that a means of reducing flow noise was required.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The first were made of canvas on a framework, then steel ones were used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Now domes are usually made of reinforced plastic or pressurized rubber.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Such sonars are primarily active in operation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An example of a conventional hull mounted sonar is the SQS-56.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Because of the problems of ship noise, towed sonars are also used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] These have the advantage of being able to be placed deeper in the water, but have limitations on their use in shallow water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] These are called towed arrays (linear) or variable depth sonars (VDS) with 2/3D arrays.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A problem is that the winches required to deploy/recover them are large and expensive.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] VDS sets are primarily active in operation, while towed arrays are passive.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An example of a modern active-passive ship towed sonar is Sonar 2087 made by Thales Underwater Systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Modern torpedoes are generally fitted with an active/passive sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This may be used to home directly on the target, but wake homing torpedoes are also used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An early example of an acoustic homer was the Mark 37 torpedo.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Torpedo countermeasures can be towed or free.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An early example was the German *Sieglinde* device while the *Bold* was a chemical device.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A widely used US device was the towed AN/SLQ-25 Nixie while the mobile submarine simulator (MOSS) was a free device.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A modern alternative to the Nixie system is the UK Royal Navy S2170 Surface Ship Torpedo Defence system.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Mines may be fitted with a sonar to detect, localize and recognize the required target.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Mine countermeasure (MCM) sonar, sometimes called "mine and obstacle avoidance sonar (MOAS)", is a specialized type of sonar used for detecting small objects.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Most MCM sonars are hull mounted but a few types are VDS design.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An example of a hull mounted MCM sonar is the Type 2193 while the SQQ-32 mine-hunting sonar and Type 2093 systems are VDS designs.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Submarines rely on sonar to a greater extent than surface ships as they cannot use radar in water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The sonar arrays may be hull mounted or towed.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Information fitted on typical fits is given in *Oyashio*-class submarine and *Swiftsure*-class submarine.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Helicopters can be used for antisubmarine warfare by deploying fields of active-passive sonobuoys or can operate dipping sonar, such as the AQS-13.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Fixed wing aircraft can also deploy sonobuoys and have greater endurance and capacity to deploy them.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Processing from the sonobuoys or dipping sonar can be on the aircraft or on ship.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Dipping sonar has the advantage of being deployable to depths appropriate to daily conditions.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Helicopters have also been used for mine countermeasure missions using towed sonars such as the AQS-20A.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Dedicated sonars can be fitted to ships and submarines for underwater communication.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The systems exploited the SOFAR channel, also known as the deep sound channel, where a sound speed minimum creates a waveguide in which low frequency sound travels thousands of miles.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Analysis was based on an AT&T sound spectrograph, which converted sound into a visual spectrogram representing a time–frequency analysis of sound that was developed for speech analysis and modified to analyze low-frequency underwater sounds.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] That process was Low Frequency Analysis and Recording and the equipment was termed the Low Frequency Analyzer and Recorder, both with the acronym LOFAR.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] LOFAR research was termed *Jezebel* and led to usage in air and surface systems, particularly sonobuoys using the process and sometimes using "Jezebel" in their name.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The proposed system offered such promise of long-range submarine detection that the Navy ordered immediate moves for implementation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Between installation of a test array followed by a full scale, forty element, prototype operational array in 1951 and 1958 systems were installed in the Atlantic and then the Pacific under the unclassified name *Project Caesar*.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The original systems were terminated at classified shore stations designated Naval Facility (NAVFAC) explained as engaging in "ocean research" to cover their classified mission.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The system was upgraded multiple times with more advanced cable allowing the arrays to be installed in ocean basins and upgraded processing.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The shore stations were eliminated in a process of consolidation and rerouting the arrays to central processing centers into the 1990s.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1985, with new mobile arrays and other systems becoming operational the collective system name was changed to Integrated Undersea Surveillance System (IUSS).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] In 1991, the mission of the system was declassified.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The year before IUSS insignia were authorized for wear.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Access was granted to some systems for scientific research.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] A similar system is believed to have been operated by the Soviet Union.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Sonar can be used to detect frogmen and other scuba divers.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This can be applicable around ships or at entrances to ports.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Active sonar can also be used as a deterrent and/or disablement mechanism.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Limpet mine imaging sonar (LIMIS) is a hand-held or ROV-mounted imaging sonar designed for patrol divers (combat frogmen or clearance divers) to look for limpet mines in low visibility water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] The LUIS is another imaging sonar for use by a diver.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] Integrated navigation sonar system (INSS) is a small flashlight-shaped handheld sonar for divers that displays range.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] This is a sonar designed to detect and locate the transmissions from hostile active sonars.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p01] An example of this is the Type 2082 fitted on the British *Vanguard*-class submarines.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Fishing is an important industry that is seeing growing demand, but world catch tonnage is falling as a result of serious resource problems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The industry faces a future of continuing worldwide consolidation until a point of sustainability can be reached.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] However, the consolidation of the fishing fleets are driving increased demands for sophisticated fish finding electronics such as sensors, sounders and sonars.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Historically, fishermen have used many different techniques to find and harvest fish.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] However, acoustic technology has been one of the most important driving forces behind the development of the modern commercial fisheries.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Sound waves travel differently through fish than through water because a fish's air-filled swim bladder has a different density than seawater.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] This density difference allows the detection of schools of fish by using reflected sound.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Acoustic technology is especially well suited for underwater applications since sound travels farther and faster underwater than in air.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Today, commercial fishing vessels rely almost completely on acoustic sonar and sounders to detect fish.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Fishermen also use active sonar and echo sounder technology to determine water depth, bottom contour, and bottom composition.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Companies such as eSonar, Raymarine, Marport Canada, Wesmar, Furuno, Krupp, and Simrad make a variety of sonar and acoustic instruments for the deep sea commercial fishing industry.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] For example, net sensors take various underwater measurements and transmit the information back to a receiver on board a vessel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Each sensor is equipped with one or more acoustic transducers depending on its specific function.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Data is transmitted from the sensors using wireless acoustic telemetry and is received by a hull mounted hydrophone.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The analog signals are decoded and converted by a digital acoustic receiver into data which is transmitted to a bridge computer for graphical display on a high resolution monitor.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Echo sounding is a process used to determine the depth of water beneath ships and boats.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] A type of active sonar, echo sounding is the transmission of an acoustic pulse directly downwards to the seabed, measuring the time between transmission and echo return, after having hit the bottom and bouncing back to its ship of origin.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The acoustic pulse is emitted by a transducer which receives the return echo as well.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The depth measurement is calculated by multiplying the speed of sound in water (averaging 1,500 meters per second) by the time between emission and echo return.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The value of underwater acoustics to the fishing industry has led to the development of other acoustic instruments that operate in a similar fashion to echo-sounders but, because their function is slightly different from the initial model of the echo-sounder, have been given different terms.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The net sounder is an echo sounder with a transducer mounted on the headline of the net rather than on the bottom of the vessel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Nevertheless, to accommodate the distance from the transducer to the display unit, which is much greater than in a normal echo-sounder, several refinements have to be made.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The first is the cable type in which the signals are sent along a cable.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] In this case, there has to be the provision of a cable drum on which to haul, shoot and stow the cable during the different phases of the operation.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The second type is the cable-less net-sounder – such as Marport's Trawl Explorer – in which the signals are sent acoustically between the net and hull mounted receiver-hydrophone on the vessel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] In this case, no cable drum is required but sophisticated electronics are needed at the transducer and receiver.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The display on a net sounder shows the distance of the net from the bottom (or the surface), rather than the depth of water as with the echo-sounder's hull-mounted transducer.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Fixed to the headline of the net, the footrope can usually be seen which gives an indication of the net performance.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Any fish passing into the net can also be seen, allowing fine adjustments to be made to catch the most fish possible.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] In other fisheries, where the amount of fish in the net is important, catch sensor transducers are mounted at various positions on the cod-end of the net.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] As the cod-end fills up these catch sensor transducers are triggered one by one and this information is transmitted acoustically to display monitors on the bridge of the vessel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The skipper can then decide when to haul the net.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Modern versions of the net sounder, using multiple element transducers, function more like a sonar than an echo sounder and show slices of the area in front of the net and not merely the vertical view that the initial net sounders used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The sonar is an echo-sounder with a directional capability that can show fish or other objects around the vessel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Small sonars have been fitted to remotely operated vehicles (ROVs) and unmanned underwater vehicles (UUVs) to allow their operation in murky conditions.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] These sonars are used for looking ahead of the vehicle.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The AN/BLQ-11 Long-Term Mine Reconnaissance System is a UUV for MCM purposes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Sonars which act as beacons are fitted to aircraft to allow their location in the event of a crash in the sea.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Short and long baseline sonars may be used for caring out the location, such as LBL.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] In 2013 an inventor in the United States unveiled a "spider-sense" bodysuit, equipped with ultrasonic sensors and haptic feedback systems, which alerts the wearer of incoming threats; allowing them to respond to attackers even when blindfolded.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Detection of fish, and other marine and aquatic life, and estimation their individual sizes or total biomass using active sonar techniques.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Sound pulses reflect off any object that has a different density than the surrounding medium.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] This includes fish, or more specifically, the air-filled swim bladder on fish.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] These echoes provide information on fish size, location, abundance and behavior.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] This is especially effective for fish swim bladders (e.g. herring, cod, and pollock), and less useful for fish without them (e.g. sharks, mackerel, and flounder).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Data from the watercolumn is usually processed differently than seafloor or object detection data, this data type can be processed with specialized software.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] An upward looking echo sounder mounted on the bottom or on a platform may be used to make measurements of wave height and period.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] From this statistics of the surface conditions at a location can be derived.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Special short range sonars have been developed to allow measurements of water velocity.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Sonars have been developed that can be used to characterise the sea bottom into, for example, mud, sand, and gravel.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Relatively simple sonars such as echo sounders can be promoted to seafloor classification systems via add-on modules, converting echo parameters into sediment type.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Different algorithms exist, but they are all based on changes in the energy or shape of the reflected sounder pings.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Advanced substrate classification analysis can be achieved using calibrated (scientific) echosounders and parametric or fuzzy-logic analysis of the acoustic data.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Side-scan sonars can be used to derive maps of seafloor topography (bathymetry) by moving the sonar across it just above the bottom.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Low frequency sonars such as GLORIA have been used for continental shelf wide surveys while high frequency sonars are used for more detailed surveys of smaller areas.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Hull-mounted multibeam echosounders on large surface vessels produce swathes of bathymetric data in near real time.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] One example, the General Instrument "Seabeam" system, uses a projector array along the keel to ensonify the bottom with a fan beam.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Signals from a hydrophone array mounted athwartships are processed to synthesize multiple virtual fan beams crossing the projector beam at right angles.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Creating two and three-dimensional images using sonar data.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Powerful low frequency echo-sounders have been developed for providing profiles of the upper layers of the ocean bottom.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] One of the most recent devices is Innomar's SES-2000 quattro multi-transducer parametric SBP, used for example in the Puck Bay for underwater archaeological purposes.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Gas bubbles can leak from the seabed, or close to it, from multiple sources.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] These can be detected by both passive and active sonar (shown in schematic figure by yellow and red systems respectively).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Natural seeps of methane and carbon dioxide occur.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Gas pipelines can leak, and it is important to be able to detect whether leakage occurs from Carbon Capture and Storage Facilities (CCSFs; e.g. depleted oil wells into which extracted atmospheric carbon is stored).
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Quantification of the amount of gas leaking is difficult, and although estimates can be made use active and passive sonar, it is important to question their accuracy because of the assumptions inherent in making such estimations from sonar data.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Various synthetic aperture sonars have been built in the laboratory and some have entered use in mine-hunting and search systems.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] An explanation of their operation is given in synthetic aperture sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Parametric sources use the non-linearity of water to generate the difference frequency between two high frequencies.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Such a projector has advantages of broad bandwidth, narrow beamwidth, and when fully developed and carefully measured it has no obvious sidelobes: see Parametric array.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Its major disadvantage is very low efficiency of only a few percent.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Westervelt summarizes the trends involved.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The use of both active and passive sonar has been proposed for various extraterrestrial environments.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] One example is Titan, where active sonar could be used to determine the depth of its hydrocarbon seas, and passive sonar could be used to detect methanefalls.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Proposals that do not take proper account of the difference between terrestrial and extraterrestrial environments could lead to erroneous measurements.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Research has shown that use of active sonar can lead to mass strandings of marine mammals.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Beaked whales, the most common casualty of the strandings, have been shown to be highly sensitive to mid-frequency active sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Other marine mammals such as the blue whale also flee from the source of the sonar, while naval activity was suggested to be the most probable cause of a mass stranding of dolphins.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The US Navy, which part-funded some of the studies, said that the findings only showed behavioural responses to sonar, not actual harm, but they "will evaluate the effectiveness of [their] marine mammal protective measures in light of new research findings".
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] A 2008 US Supreme Court ruling on the use of sonar by the US Navy noted that there had been no cases where sonar had been conclusively shown to have harmed or killed a marine mammal.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Some marine animals, such as whales and dolphins, use echolocation systems, sometimes called *biosonar* to locate predators and prey.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Research on the effects of sonar on blue whales in the Southern California Bight shows that mid-frequency sonar use disrupts the whales' feeding behavior.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] This indicates that sonar-induced disruption of feeding and displacement from high-quality prey patches could have significant and previously undocumented impacts on baleen whale foraging ecology, individual fitness and population health.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] A review of evidence on the mass strandings of beaked whale linked to naval exercises where sonar was used was published in 2019.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] It concluded that the effects of mid-frequency active sonar are strongest on Cuvier's beaked whales but vary among individuals or populations.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The review suggested the strength of response of individual animals may depend on whether they had prior exposure to sonar, and that symptoms of decompression sickness have been found in stranded whales that may be a result of such response to sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] It noted that in the Canary Islands where multiple strandings had been previously reported, no more mass strandings had occurred once naval exercises during which sonar was used were banned in the area, and recommended that the ban be extended to other areas where mass strandings continue to occur.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Low frequency sonar can create a small temporary shift in the hearing threshold of some fish.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The frequencies of sonars range from infrasonic to above a megahertz.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Generally, the lower frequencies have longer range, while the higher frequencies offer better resolution, and smaller size for a given directionality.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] To achieve reasonable directionality, frequencies below 1 kHz generally require large size, usually achieved as towed arrays.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Low frequency sonars are loosely defined as 1–5 kHz, albeit some navies regard 5–7 kHz also as low frequency.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Medium frequency is defined as 5–15 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Another style of division considers low frequency to be under 1 kHz, and medium frequency at between 1–10 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] American World War II era sonars operated at a relatively high frequency of 20–30 kHz, to achieve directionality with reasonably small transducers, with typical maximum operational range of 2,500 yd.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Postwar sonars used lower frequencies to achieve longer range; e.g.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] SQS-4 operated at 10 kHz with range up to 5,000 yd.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] SQS-26 and SQS-53 operated at 3 kHz with range up to 20,000 yd; their domes had size of approx. a 60-ft personnel boat, an upper size limit for conventional hull sonars.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Achieving larger sizes by conformal sonar array spread over the hull has not been effective so far, for lower frequencies linear or towed arrays are therefore used.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Japanese WW2 sonars operated at a range of frequencies.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The Type 91, with 30 inch quartz projector, worked at 9 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The Type 93, with smaller quartz projectors, operated at 17.5 kHz (model 5 at 16 or 19 kHz magnetostrictive) at powers between 1.7 and 2.5 kilowatts, with range of up to 6 km.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The later Type 3, with German-design magnetostrictive transducers, operated at 13, 14.5, 16, or 20 kHz (by model), using twin transducers (except model 1 which had three single ones), at 0.2 to 2.5 kilowatts.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The simple type used 14.5 kHz magnetostrictive transducers at 0.25 kW, driven by capacitive discharge instead of oscillators, with range up to 2.5 km.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] The sonar's resolution is angular; objects further apart are imaged with lower resolutions than nearby ones.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Another source lists ranges and resolutions vs frequencies for sidescan sonars.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] 30 kHz provides low resolution with range of 1000–6,000 m, 100 kHz gives medium resolution at 500–1,000 m, 300 kHz gives high resolution at 150–500 m, and 600 kHz gives high resolution at 75–150 m.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Longer range sonars are more adversely affected by nonhomogenities of water.
[src:sonar-systems/passive-sonar-p02] Some environments, typically shallow waters near the coasts, have complicated terrain with many features; higher frequencies become necessary there.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Side-scan sonar is used to image large areas of the seafloor quickly.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Applications include surveys for marine archaeology, shipwreck hunting, search and recovery (SAR), and environmental monitoring.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In conjunction with seafloor samples, it is able to provide an understanding of the differences in material and texture type of the seabed.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Side-scan sonar imagery is also a commonly used tool to detect debris items and other obstructions on the seafloor that may be hazardous to shipping or to seafloor installations by the oil and gas industry.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In addition, the status of pipelines and cables on the seafloor can be investigated using side-scan sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Side-scan data are frequently acquired along with bathymetric soundings and sub-bottom profiler data, thus providing a glimpse of the shallow structure of the seabed.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Side-scan sonar is also used for fisheries research, dredging operations and environmental studies.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] It also has military applications including mine detection.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Side-scan uses a sonar device that emits conical or fan-shaped pulses down toward the seafloor across a wide angle perpendicular to the path of the sensor through the water, which may be towed from a surface vessel or submarine (called a “towfish”), or mounted on the ship's hull.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] The intensity of the acoustic reflections from the seafloor of this fan-shaped beam is recorded in a series of cross-track slices.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] When stitched together along the direction of motion, these slices form an image of the sea bottom within the swath (coverage width) of the beam.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] The sound frequencies used in side-scan sonar usually range from 100 to 500 kHz; higher frequencies yield better resolution but less range.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] The earliest side-scan sonars used a single conical-beam transducer.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Next, units were made with two transducers to cover both sides.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] The transducers were either contained in one hull-mounted package or with two packages on either side of the vessel.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Next the transducers evolved to fan-shaped beams to produce a better "sonogram" or sonar image.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In order to get closer to the bottom in deep water the side-scan transducers were placed in a "tow fish" and pulled by a tow cable.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Up until the mid-1980s, commercial side scan images were produced on paper records.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] The early paper records were produced with a sweeping plotter that burned the image into a scrolling paper record.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Later plotters allowed for the simultaneous plotting of position and ship motion information onto the paper record.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In the late 1980s, commercial systems using the newer, cheaper computer systems developed digital scan-converters that could mimic more cheaply the analog scan converters used by the military systems to produce TV and computer displayed images of the scan, and store them on video tape.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Currently data is stored on computer hard drives or solid-state media - the data is typically displayed in grayscale or color images, known as side scan sonograms, which provide a visual representation of the underwater environment.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] One of the inventors of side-scan sonar was German scientist, Dr.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Julius Hagemann, who was brought to the US after World War II and worked at the US Navy Mine Defense Laboratory, Panama City, FL from 1947 until his death in 1964.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] His work is documented in US Patent 4,197,591 which was first disclosed in Aug 1958, but remained classified by the US Navy until it was finally issued in 1980.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Experimental side-scan sonar systems were made during the 1950s in laboratories including Scripps Institution of Oceanography and Hudson Laboratories and by Dr.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Military side-scan sonars were made in the 1950s by Westinghouse.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Advanced systems were later developed and built for special military purposes, such as to find H-Bombs lost at sea or to find a lost Russian submarine, at the Westinghouse facility in Annapolis up through the 1990s.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] This group also produced the first and only working *Angle Look Sonar* that could trace objects while looking under the vehicle.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] The first commercial side-scan system was the Kelvin Hughes "Transit Sonar", a converted echo-sounder with a single-channel, pole-mounted, fan-beam transducer introduced around 1960.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Harold Edgerton, Edward Curley, and John Yules used a conical-beam 12 kHz side-scan sonar to find the sunken Vineyard Lightship in Buzzards Bay, Massachusetts.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] A team led by Martin Klein at Edgerton, Germeshausen & Grier (later E.G. & G., Inc.) developed the first successful towed, dual-channel commercial side-scan sonar system from 1963 to 1966.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Martin Klein is generally considered to be the "father" of commercial side-scan sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In 1967, Edgerton used Klein's sonar to help Alexander McKee find Henry VIII's flagship *Mary Rose*.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] That same year Klein used the sonar to help archaeologist George Bass find a 2000-year-old ship off the coast of Turkey.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In 1968 Klein founded Klein Associates (now KLEIN - A MIND Technology Business) and continued to work on improvements including the first commercial high frequency (500 kHz) systems and the first dual-frequency side-scan sonars, and the first combined side-scan and sub-bottom profiling sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] In 1985, Charles Mazel of Klein Associates (now Klein Marine Systems, Inc.) produced the first commercial side-scan sonar training videos and the first *Side Scan Sonar Training Manual* and two oceanographers found the wreck of the RMS *Titanic*.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] For surveying large areas, the GLORIA sidescan sonar was developed by Marconi Underwater Systems and the Institute of Oceanographic Sciences (IOS) for NERC.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] GLORIA stands for Geological Long Range Inclined Asdic.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] It was used by the US Geological Survey and the IOS in the UK to obtain images of continental shelves worldwide.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] It operated at relatively low frequencies to obtain long range.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] Like most side-scan sonars, the GLORIA instrument is towed behind a ship.
[src:sonar-systems/side-scan-sonar] GLORIA has a ping rate of two per minute, and detects returns from a range of up to 22 km either side of the sonar fish.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Hydroacoustics, using sonar technology, is most commonly used for monitoring of underwater physical and biological characteristics.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Hydroacoustics can be used to detect the depth of a water body (bathymetry), as well as the presence or absence, abundance, distribution, size, and behavior of underwater plants and animals.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Hydroacoustic sensing involves "passive acoustics" (listening for sounds) or *active acoustics* making a sound and listening for the echo, hence the common name for the device, echo sounder or echosounder.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] There are a number of different causes of noise from shipping.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These can be subdivided into those caused by the propeller, those caused by machinery, and those caused by the movement of the hull through the water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The relative importance of these three different categories will depend, amongst other things, on the ship type.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] One of the main causes of hydro acoustic noise from fully submerged lifting surfaces is the unsteady separated turbulent flow near the surface's trailing edge that produces pressure fluctuations on the surface and unsteady oscillatory flow in the near wake.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The relative motion between the surface and the ocean creates a turbulent boundary layer (TBL) that surrounds the surface.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The noise is generated by the fluctuating velocity and pressure fields within this TBL.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The field of underwater acoustics is closely related to a number of other fields of acoustic study, including sonar, transduction, signal processing, acoustical oceanography, bioacoustics, and physical acoustics.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Underwater sound has probably been used by marine animals for millions of years.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In 1687 Isaac Newton wrote his *Mathematical Principles of Natural Philosophy* which included the first mathematical treatment of sound.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The next major step in the development of underwater acoustics was made by Daniel Colladon, a Swiss physicist, and Charles Sturm, a French mathematician.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In 1826, on Lake Geneva, they measured the elapsed time between a flash of light and the sound of a submerged ship's bell heard using an underwater listening horn.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] They measured a sound speed of 1435 metres per second over a 17 kilometre (km) distance, providing the first quantitative measurement of sound speed in water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The result they obtained was within about 2% of currently accepted values.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In 1877 Lord Rayleigh wrote the *Theory of Sound* and established modern acoustic theory.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The sinking of *Titanic* in 1912 and the start of World War I provided the impetus for the next wave of progress in underwater acoustics.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Systems for detecting icebergs and U-boats were developed.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Between 1912 and 1914, a number of echolocation patents were granted in Europe and the U.S., culminating in Reginald A.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Pioneering work was carried out during this time in France by Paul Langevin and in Britain by A B Wood and associates.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The development of both active ASDIC and passive sonar (SOund Navigation And Ranging) proceeded apace during the war, driven by the first large scale deployments of submarines.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Other advances in underwater acoustics included the development of acoustic mines.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In 1919, the first scientific paper on underwater acoustics was published, theoretically describing the refraction of sound waves produced by temperature and salinity gradients in the ocean.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The range predictions of the paper were experimentally validated by propagation loss measurements.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The next two decades saw the development of several applications of underwater acoustics.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The fathometer, or depth sounder, was developed commercially during the 1920s.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Originally natural materials were used for the transducers, but by the 1930s sonar systems incorporating piezoelectric transducers made from synthetic materials were being used for passive listening systems and for active echo-ranging systems.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These systems were used to good effect during World War II by both submarines and anti-submarine vessels.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Many advances in underwater acoustics were made which were summarised later in the series *Physics of Sound in the Sea*, published in 1946.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] After World War II, the development of sonar systems was driven largely by the Cold War, resulting in advances in the theoretical and practical understanding of underwater acoustics, aided by computer-based techniques.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A sound wave propagating underwater consists of alternating compressions and rarefactions of the water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These compressions and rarefactions are detected by a receiver, such as the human ear or a hydrophone, as changes in pressure.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These waves may be man-made or naturally generated.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The speed of sound $c\,$ (i.e., the longitudinal motion of wavefronts) is related to frequency $f\,$ and wavelength $\lambda \,$ of a wave by $c=f\cdot \lambda$ .
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] This is different from the particle velocity $u\,$ , which refers to the motion of molecules in the medium due to the sound, and relates the plane wave pressure $p\,$ to the fluid density $\rho \,$ and sound speed $c\,$ by $p=c\cdot u\cdot \rho$ .
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The product of c and $\rho \,$ from the above formula is known as the characteristic acoustic impedance.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The acoustic power (energy per second) crossing unit area is known as the intensity of the wave and for a plane wave the average intensity is given by $I=q^{2}/(\rho c)\,$ , where $q\,$ is the root mean square acoustic pressure.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At 1 kHz, the wavelength in water is about 1.5 m.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sometimes the term "sound velocity" is used but this is incorrect as the quantity is a scalar.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The large impedance contrast between air and water (the ratio is about 3600) and the scale of surface roughness means that the sea surface behaves as an almost perfect reflector of sound at frequencies below 1 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sound speed in water exceeds that in air by a factor of 4.4 and the density ratio is about 820.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Absorption of low frequency sound is weak.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] (see Technical Guides – Calculation of absorption of sound in seawater for an on-line calculator).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The main cause of sound attenuation in fresh water, and at high frequency in sea water (above 100 kHz) is viscosity.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Additional contributions at lower frequency in seawater are associated with the ionic relaxation of boric acid (up to c.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sound may be absorbed by losses at the fluid boundaries.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Near the surface of the sea losses can occur in a bubble layer or in ice, while at the bottom sound can penetrate into the sediment and be absorbed.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Both the water surface and bottom are reflecting and scattering boundaries.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For many purposes the sea-air surface can be thought of as a perfect reflector.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The impedance contrast is so great that little energy is able to cross this boundary.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Acoustic pressure waves reflected from the sea surface experience a reversal in phase, often stated as either a "pi phase change" or a "180 deg phase change".
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] This is represented mathematically by assigning a reflection coefficient of minus 1 instead of plus one to the sea surface.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At high frequency (above about 1 kHz) or when the sea is rough, some of the incident sound is scattered, and this is taken into account by assigning a reflection coefficient whose magnitude is less than one.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For example, close to normal incidence, the reflection coefficient becomes $R=-e^{-2k^{2}h^{2}\sin ^{2}A}$ , where *h* is the rms wave height.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A further complication is the presence of wind-generated bubbles or fish close to the sea surface.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The bubbles can also form plumes that absorb some of the incident and scattered sound, and scatter some of the sound themselves.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The acoustic impedance mismatch between water and the bottom is generally much less than at the surface and is more complex.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] It depends on the bottom material types and depth of the layers.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Theories have been developed for predicting the sound propagation in the bottom in this case, for example by Biot and by Buckingham.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The reflection of sound at a target whose dimensions are large compared with the acoustic wavelength depends on its size and shape as well as the impedance of the target relative to that of water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Formulae have been developed for the target strength of various simple shapes as a function of angle of sound incidence.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] More complex shapes may be approximated by combining these simple ones.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Underwater acoustic propagation depends on many factors.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The direction of sound propagation is determined by the sound speed gradients in the water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These speed gradients transform the sound wave through refraction, reflection, and dispersion.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In the sea the vertical gradients are generally much larger than the horizontal ones.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Combining this with a tendency towards increasing sound speed at increasing depth, due to the increasing pressure in the deep sea, causes a reversal of the sound speed gradient in the thermocline, creating an efficient waveguide at the depth, corresponding to the minimum sound speed.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The sound speed profile may cause regions of low sound intensity called "Shadow Zones", and regions of high intensity called "Caustics".
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These may be found by ray tracing methods.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At the equator and temperate latitudes in the ocean, the surface temperature is high enough to reverse the pressure effect, such that a sound speed minimum occurs at depth of a few hundred meters.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The presence of this minimum creates a special channel known as deep sound channel, or SOFAR (sound fixing and ranging) channel, permitting guided propagation of underwater sound for thousands of kilometers without interaction with the sea surface or the seabed.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Another phenomenon in the deep sea is the formation of sound focusing areas, known as convergence zones.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In this case sound is refracted downward from a near-surface source and then back up again.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The horizontal distance from the source at which this occurs depends on the positive and negative sound speed gradients.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A surface duct can also occur in both deep and moderately shallow water when there is upward refraction, for example due to cold surface temperatures.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Propagation is by repeated sound bounces off the surface.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In general, as sound propagates underwater there is a reduction in the sound intensity over increasing ranges, though in some circumstances a gain can be obtained due to focusing.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] *Propagation loss* (sometimes referred to as *transmission loss*) is a quantitative measure of the reduction in sound intensity between two points, normally the sound source and a distant receiver.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] If $I_{s}$ is the far field intensity of the source referred to a point 1 m from its acoustic center and $I_{r}$ is the intensity at the receiver, then the propagation loss is given by ${\mathit {PL}}=10\log(I_{s}/I_{r})$ .
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In this equation $I_{r}$ is not the true acoustic intensity at the receiver, which is a vector quantity, but a scalar equal to the equivalent plane wave intensity (EPWI) of the sound field.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The EPWI is defined as the magnitude of the intensity of a plane wave of the same RMS pressure as the true acoustic field.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At short range the propagation loss is dominated by spreading while at long range it is dominated by absorption and/or scattering losses.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] An alternative definition is possible in terms of pressure instead of intensity, giving ${\mathit {PL}}=20\log(p_{s}/p_{r})$ , where $p_{s}$ is the RMS acoustic pressure in the far-field of the projector, scaled to a standard distance of 1 m, and $p_{r}$ is the RMS pressure at the receiver position.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These two definitions are not exactly equivalent because the characteristic impedance at the receiver may be different from that at the source.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Because of this, the use of the intensity definition leads to a different sonar equation to the definition based on a pressure ratio.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] If the source and receiver are both in water, the difference is small.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The propagation of sound through water is described by the wave equation, with appropriate boundary conditions.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A number of models have been developed to simplify propagation calculations.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These models include ray theory, normal mode solutions, and parabolic equation simplifications of the wave equation.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Each set of solutions is generally valid and computationally efficient in a limited frequency and range regime, and may involve other limits as well.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Ray theory is more appropriate at short range and high frequency, while the other solutions function better at long range and low frequency.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Various empirical and analytical formulae have also been derived from measurements that are useful approximations.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Transient sounds result in a decaying background that can be of much larger duration than the original transient signal.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The cause of this background, known as reverberation, is partly due to scattering from rough boundaries and partly due to scattering from fish and other biota.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For an acoustic signal to be detected easily, it must exceed the reverberation level as well as the background noise level.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] If an underwater object is moving relative to an underwater receiver, the frequency of the received sound is different from that of the sound radiated (or reflected) by the object.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] This change in frequency is known as a Doppler shift.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The shift can be easily observed in active sonar systems, particularly narrow-band ones, because the transmitter frequency is known, and the relative motion between sonar and object can be calculated.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sometimes the frequency of the radiated noise (a tonal) may also be known, in which case the same calculation can be done for passive sonar.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For active systems the change in frequency is 0.69 Hz per knot per kHz and half this for passive systems as propagation is only one way.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The shift corresponds to an increase in frequency for an approaching target.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Though acoustic propagation modelling generally predicts a constant received sound level, in practice there are both temporal and spatial fluctuations.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These may be due to both small and large scale environmental phenomena.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These can include sound speed profile fine structure and frontal zones as well as internal waves.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Because in general there are multiple propagation paths between a source and receiver, small phase changes in the interference pattern between these paths can lead to large fluctuations in sound intensity.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In water, especially with air bubbles, the change in density due to a change in pressure is not exactly linearly proportional.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] As a consequence for a sinusoidal wave input additional harmonic and subharmonic frequencies are generated.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] When two sinusoidal waves are input, sum and difference frequencies are generated.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The conversion process is greater at high source levels than small ones.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Because of the non-linearity there is a dependence of sound speed on the pressure amplitude so that large changes travel faster than small ones.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Thus a sinusoidal waveform gradually becomes a sawtooth one with a steep rise and a gradual tail.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Use is made of this phenomenon in parametric sonar and theories have been developed to account for this, e.g. by Westerfield.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sound in water is measured using a hydrophone, which is the underwater equivalent of a microphone.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A hydrophone measures pressure fluctuations, and these are usually converted to sound pressure level (SPL), which is a logarithmic measure of the mean square acoustic pressure.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The scale for acoustic pressure in water differs from that used for sound in air.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In air the reference pressure is 20 μPa rather than 1 μPa.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For the same numerical value of SPL, the intensity of a plane wave (power per unit area, proportional to mean square sound pressure divided by acoustic impedance) in air is about 202×3600 = 1 440 000 times higher than in water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Similarly, the intensity is about the same if the SPL is 61.6 dB higher in the water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The 2017 standard ISO 18405 defines terms and expressions used in the field of underwater acoustics, including the calculation of underwater sound pressure levels.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Approximate values for fresh water and seawater, respectively, at atmospheric pressure are 1450 and 1500 m/s for the sound speed, and 1000 and 1030 kg/m3 for the density.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The speed of sound in water increases with increasing pressure, temperature and salinity.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The maximum speed in pure water under atmospheric pressure is attained at about 74 °C; sound travels slower in hotter water after that point; the maximum increases with pressure.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Many measurements have been made of sound absorption in lakes and the ocean (see Technical Guides – Calculation of absorption of sound in seawater for an on-line calculator).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Measurement of acoustic signals are possible if their amplitude exceeds a minimum threshold, determined partly by the signal processing used and partly by the level of background noise.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Ambient noise is that part of the received noise that is independent of the source, receiver and platform characteristics.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Thus it excludes reverberation and towing noise for example.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The background noise present in the ocean, or ambient noise, has many different sources and varies with location and frequency.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At the lowest frequencies, from about 0.1 Hz to 10 Hz, ocean turbulence and microseisms are the primary contributors to the noise background.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Typical noise spectrum levels decrease with increasing frequency from about 140 dB re 1 μPa2/Hz at 1 Hz to about 30 dB re 1 μPa2/Hz at 100 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Distant ship traffic is one of the dominant noise sources in most areas for frequencies of around 100 Hz, while wind-induced surface noise is the main source between 1 kHz and 30 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At very high frequencies, above 100 kHz, thermal noise of water molecules begins to dominate.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The thermal noise spectral level at 100 kHz is 25 dB re 1 μPa2/Hz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The spectral density of thermal noise increases by 20 dB per decade (approximately 6 dB per octave).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Transient sound sources also contribute to ambient noise.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] These can include intermittent geological activity, such as earthquakes and underwater volcanoes, rainfall on the surface, and biological activity.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Biological sources include cetaceans (especially blue, fin and sperm whales), certain types of fish, and snapping shrimp.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Rain can produce high levels of ambient noise.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] However the numerical relationship between rain rate and ambient noise level is difficult to determine because measurement of rain rate is problematic at sea.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Many measurements have been made of sea surface, bottom and volume reverberation.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Empirical models have sometimes been derived from these.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A commonly used expression for the band 0.4 to 6.4 kHz is that by Chapman and Harris.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] It is found that a sinusoidal waveform is spread in frequency due to the surface motion.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For bottom reverberation a Lambert's Law is found often to apply approximately, for example see Mackenzie.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Volume reverberation is usually found to occur mainly in layers, which change depth with the time of day, e.g., see Marshall and Chapman.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The under-surface of ice can produce strong reverberation when it is rough, see for example Milne.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Bottom loss has been measured as a function of grazing angle for many frequencies in various locations, for example those by the US Marine Geophysical Survey.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The loss depends on the sound speed in the bottom (which is affected by gradients and layering) and by roughness.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Graphs have been produced for the loss to be expected in particular circumstances.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In shallow water bottom loss often has the dominant impact on long range propagation.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] At low frequencies sound can propagate through the sediment then back into the water.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] As with airborne sound, sound pressure level (SPL) underwater is usually reported in units of decibels, but there are differences that make it difficult (and often inappropriate) to compare SPL in water with SPL in air.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The lowest audible SPL for a human diver with normal hearing is about 67 dB re 1 μPa, with greatest sensitivity occurring at frequencies around 1 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] This corresponds to a sound intensity 5.4 dB, or 3.5 times, higher than the threshold in air (see Measurements above).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] High levels of underwater sound create a potential hazard to human divers.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Guidelines for exposure of human divers to underwater sound are reported by the SOLMAR project of the NATO Undersea Research Centre.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Human divers exposed to SPL above 154 dB re 1 μPa in the frequency range 0.6 to 2.5 kHz are reported to experience changes in their heart rate or breathing frequency.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Diver aversion to low frequency sound is dependent upon sound pressure level and center frequency.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Dolphins and other toothed whales are known for their acute hearing sensitivity, especially in the frequency range 5 to 50 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Several species have hearing thresholds between 30 and 50 dB re 1 μPa in this frequency range.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For example, the hearing threshold of the killer whale occurs at an RMS acoustic pressure of 0.02 mPa (and frequency 15 kHz), corresponding to an SPL threshold of 26 dB re 1 μPa.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] High levels of underwater sound create a potential hazard to marine and amphibious animals.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The effects of exposure to underwater noise are reviewed by Southall et al.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The hearing sensitivity of fish is reviewed by Ladich and Fay.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The hearing threshold of the soldier fish, is 0.32 mPa (50 dB re 1 μPa) at 1.3 kHz.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The effects of exposure to underwater noise are reviewed by Popper et al.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The lobster has a hearing threshold of 1.3 Pa at 70 Hz (122 dB re 1 μPa).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Several aquatic bird species have been observed to react to underwater sound in the 1–4 kHz range, which follows the frequency range of best hearing sensitivities of birds in air.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Seaducks and cormorants have been trained to respond to sounds of 1–4 kHz with lowest hearing threshold (highest sensitivity) of 71 dB re 1 μPa (cormorants) and 105 dB re 1 μPa (seaducks).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sonar is the name given to the acoustic equivalent of radar.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Pulses of sound are used to probe the sea, and the echoes are then processed to extract information about the sea, its boundaries and submerged objects.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] An alternative use, known as *passive sonar*, attempts to do the same by listening to the sounds radiated by underwater objects.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The need for underwater acoustic telemetry exists in applications such as data harvesting for environmental monitoring, communication with and between crewed and uncrewed underwater vehicles, transmission of diver speech, etc.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A related application is **underwater remote control**, in which acoustic telemetry is used to remotely actuate a switch or trigger an event.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A prominent example of underwater remote control are acoustic releases, devices that are used to return sea floor deployed instrument packages or other payloads to the surface per remote command at the end of a deployment.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Acoustic communications form an active field of research with significant challenges to overcome, especially in horizontal, shallow-water channels.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Compared with radio telecommunications, the available bandwidth is reduced by several orders of magnitude.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The low speed of sound causes multipath propagation to stretch over time delay intervals of tens or hundreds of milliseconds, as well as significant Doppler shifts and spreading.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Often acoustic communication systems are not limited by noise, but by reverberation and time variability beyond the capability of receiver algorithms.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The fidelity of underwater communication links can be greatly improved by the use of hydrophone arrays, which allow processing techniques such as adaptive beamforming and diversity combining.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Underwater navigation and tracking is a common requirement for exploration and work by divers, ROV, autonomous underwater vehicles (AUV), crewed submersibles and submarines alike.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Unlike most radio signals which are quickly absorbed, sound propagates far underwater and at a rate that can be precisely measured or estimated.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] It can thus be used to measure distances between a tracked target and one or multiple reference of *baseline stations* precisely, and triangulate the position of the target, sometimes with centimeter accuracy.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Starting in the 1960s, this has given rise to underwater acoustic positioning systems which are now widely used.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Seismic exploration involves the use of low frequency sound (< 100 Hz) to probe deep into the seabed.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Despite the relatively poor resolution due to their long wavelength, low frequency sounds are preferred because high frequencies are heavily attenuated when they travel through the seabed.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sound sources used include airguns, vibroseis and explosives.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Acoustic sensors can be used to monitor the sound made by wind and precipitation.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For example, an acoustic rain gauge is described by Nystuen.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Acoustic thermometry of ocean climate (ATOC) uses low frequency sound to measure the global ocean temperature.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Interest in developing echo ranging systems began in earnest following the sinking of the RMS Titanic in 1912.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] By sending a sound wave ahead of a ship, the theory went, a return echo bouncing off the submerged portion of an iceberg should give early warning of collisions.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] By directing the same type of beam downwards, the depth to the bottom of the ocean could be calculated.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The first practical deep-ocean echo sounder was invented by Harvey C.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For the first time, it was possible to create a quasi-continuous profile of the ocean floor along the course of a ship.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The first such profile was made by Hayes on board the U.S.S.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Stewart, a Navy destroyer that sailed from Newport to Gibraltar between June 22 and 29, 1922.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] During that week, 900 deep-ocean soundings were made.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Using a refined echo sounder, the German survey ship Meteor made several passes across the South Atlantic from the equator to Antarctica between 1925 and 1927, taking soundings every 5 to 20 miles.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Their work created the first detailed map of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] It showed that the Ridge was a rugged mountain range, and not the smooth plateau that some scientists had envisioned.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Since that time, both naval and research vessels have operated echo sounders almost continuously while at sea.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The earliest and most widespread use of sound and sonar technology to study the properties of the sea is the use of a rainbow echo sounder to measure water depth.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Sounders were the devices used that mapped the many miles of the Santa Barbara Harbor ocean floor until 1993.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Fathometers measure the depth of the waters.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] It works by electronically sending sounds from ships, therefore also receiving the sound waves that bounces back from the bottom of the ocean.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A paper chart moves through the fathometer and is calibrated to record the depth.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] As technology advances, the development of high resolution sonars in the second half of the 20th century made it possible to not just detect underwater objects but to classify them and even image them.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Electronic sensors are now attached to ROVs since nowadays, ships or robot submarines have Remotely Operated Vehicles (ROVs).
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] There are cameras attached to these devices giving out accurate images.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The oceanographers are able to get a clear and precise quality of pictures.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] The 'pictures' can also be sent from sonars by having sound reflected off ocean surroundings.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Oftentimes sound waves reflect off animals, giving information which can be documented into deeper animal behaviour studies.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Hydrophones are used as passive listening instruments for acoustical oceanography by building an acoustical image of the underwater soundscape.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Due to its excellent propagation properties, underwater sound is used as a tool to aid the study of marine life, from microplankton to the blue whale.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Echo sounders are often used to provide data on marine life abundance, distribution, and behavior information.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Echo sounders, also referred to as hydroacoustics is also used for fish location, quantity, size, and biomass.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] Acoustic telemetry is also used for monitoring fish and marine wildlife.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] An acoustic transmitter is attached to the fish (sometimes internally) while an array of receivers listen to the information conveyed by the sound wave.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] This enables the researchers to track the movements of individuals in a small-medium scale.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] A neutrino is a fundamental particle that interacts very weakly with other matter.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] For this reason, it requires detection apparatus on a very large scale, and the ocean is sometimes used for this purpose.
[src:sonar-systems/underwater-acoustics] In particular, it is thought that ultra-high energy neutrinos in seawater can be detected acoustically.
